{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 162 "As you m
ay have noted the addition/subtraction operatios where carried out whi
le the multiplication/division operations were just indicated.  The Ma
ple commands  " }{TEXT 264 6 "expand" }{TEXT -1 6 " and  " }{TEXT 265 
8 "simplify" }{TEXT -1 298 "  can be used to rearrange and manipulate \+
algebraic sums and products of polynomial expressions.  Go back to eac
h of your calculations of a., b., c. and d. and add to each line a com
mand to expand the calculation and a command to simplify the caclulati
on.  E.g.,  the line for a. would change from:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 1 " " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 4 "f*g;" }}}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 3 "to " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 
1 0 32 "f*g; expand(f*g); simplify(f*g);" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 17 "Note the effect  " }{TEXT 268 6 "e
xpand" }{TEXT -1 5 " and " }{TEXT 269 8 "simplify" }{TEXT -1 42 "  hav
e on the way the calculation appears." }}{PARA 258 "" 0 "" {TEXT 306 
195 "The expand command does all the arithmetic, while the simplify co
mmand removes common factors.  Many times the simplify command results
 in the same expression as the original calculation results." }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 19 "The Maple commands " }{TEXT 266 16 "expand, sim
plify" }{TEXT -1 5 " and " }{TEXT 267 6 "normal" }{TEXT -1 483 " can b
e use to rearrange, manipulate and simplify (cancel common factors) al
gebraic sums, products and quotients of rational expressions.   When a
 rational expression is normalized, any common factors are cancelled. \+
 Go back to each of your calculations of e., f., g., h. and i. and add
 to each line a command to expand the calculation, to normalize the ca
lculation, to simplify the calculation and both expand and normalize t
he calculation.  E.g., the line for e. would change from:" }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 6 "F*H/G;
" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 2 "to" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 99 "F*H/G; expand(F*H/G); normal(F*H/G); simplify(F*H/G);
 expand(normal(F*H/G)); normal(expand(F*H/G));" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 17 "Note the effect  " }
{TEXT 270 6 "expand" }{TEXT -1 2 ", " }{TEXT 272 6 "normal" }{TEXT -1 
3 ",  " }{TEXT 271 8 "simplify" }{TEXT -1 10 " and both " }{TEXT 273 
6 "expand" }{TEXT -1 5 " and " }{TEXT 274 6 "normal" }{TEXT -1 42 "  h
ave on the way the calculation appears." }}{PARA 259 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
307 149 "***Many times the normal and simplify commands have the same \+
result, and once the expand(normal) and normal(expand) command also ha
d the same result." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 35 "2.  Factoring.  The
 Maple command  " }{TEXT 275 6 "factor" }{TEXT -1 300 " can be used to
 factor algebraic polynomial expressions and rational expressions.  Wh
en rational expressions are factors, any common factors are cancelled.
  Factor each of the polynomials f, g, h, F, G and H.  Also, factor th
e algebraic and rational expressions a., b., c., d., e., f., g., h. an
d i. " }{TEXT 310 4 "(***" }{TEXT 308 126 "I renamed f, g, h, and i to
 m, n, p, and r respectively to avoid conflict between the algebraic a
nd the rational expressions.)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
