F&F&F%F&F,F&F&" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 20 "factor(x^
5-x^2-2*x);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(%\"xG\"\"\",&F$F%F%F%
F%,**$)F$\"\"$F%F%*$)F$\"\"#F%!\"\"F$F%F-F.F%" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 650 "In those cases where Map
le did not find enough linear factors, there is a reason why Maple did
 not.  Maple makes an assumption that if the coefficients of a polynom
ial are all given exactly (as integers or rational numbers [ratios of \+
integer]), then you are only interested in finding exact factors (fact
ors where the coefficients are integers or rational numbers).  The Fun
damental Theorem of Algebra doesn't guarantee that the factors of  a p
olynomial will necessarily have the same kind of coefficients as the p
olynomial, only the polynomial can be factored.  You can force Maple t
o report additional (approximate) factors.  For example,  compare:" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 
22 "factor(x^3-5*x+x^2-5);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&%\"x
G\"\"\"F&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&\"\"&!\"\"F&" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "
" {MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "factor(h,sqrt(5));" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 
"6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"*$\"\"&#F&\"\"#F&F&,&F%F&F'!\"\"F&,&F%F&F&F&F&" }}}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 52 "What is t
he difference?  The extra-term is called a " }{TEXT 280 18 "field exte
nsion.  " }{TEXT -1 178 "Adding it tells Maple to consider additonal f
actors where the coefficients are allowed to include elements from the
 field extension.  It is fairly clear from the factoriztion of " }
{TEXT 281 1 "h" }{TEXT -1 280 " all by itself that something involving
  sqrt(5)  would have to be included.  However, there are problems whe
re there is not a obvious clue as to which specific field extension sh
ould be added.  If you are willing to accept an appropriate solution, \+
then using the field extension " }{TEXT 282 4 "real" }{TEXT -1 179 " t
ells Maple to factor the polynomial using a floating point approximati
on scheme.  For example, consider (here I am pretending I don't see th
at adding  sqrt(5) would be optimal):" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "
" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(h);" }}{PARA 11 "
" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&%\"xG\"\"\"F&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&\"\"&!\"\"F
&" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 15 "factor(h,real);" }}
{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"$\"+xz1OA!\"*F&F&,&F%F&
$F&\"\"!F&F&,&F%F&$\"+xz1OAF)!\"\"F&" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 91 "Finally, the Fundamental Theorem of A
lgebra does not guarantee that a polynomial of degree " }{TEXT 283 1 "
n" }{TEXT -1 11 " will have " }{TEXT 284 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 53 " real lin
ear factors.  Rather, only hat it will have " }{TEXT 285 1 "n" }{TEXT 
-1 134 " linear factors.  What is the difference?  Some of the factors
 may involve complex roots rather than real roots.  For example compar
e:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 16 "factor(x^4-144);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*
&,&*$)%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F)\"#7!\"\"F),&F%F)F*F)F)" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> \+
" 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "factor(F,sqrt(3));" }}{PARA 8 "" 1 "" {TEXT 
-1 79 "Error, (in factor) 2nd argument, 2*3^(1/2), is not a valid alge
braic extension\n" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 15 "factor
(F,real);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"$\"+:;5kM!
\"*F&F&,&F%F&$\"+:;5kMF)!\"\"F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&$\"+++++7!\")F&F&" }}}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "factor(F,complex);" }}{PARA 
11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#**,&%\"xG\"\"\"$\"+:;5kM!\"*F&F&,&F%F&^#F'F&
F&,&F%F&^#$!+:;5kMF)F&F&,&F%F&$\"+:;5kMF)!\"\"F&" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 126 "For the following polyno
mials demonstrate that each can be factored completely into linear fac
