the polynomials had to be factored in the complex realm to return line
ar factors." }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 
"" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 380 "A related theore
m about finding roots of polynomials (equivalently factoring polynomia
ls into a product of linear factors) asserts that if the polynomial ha
s real coefficients -- all of the polynomials we have considered (and \+
will consider) have had real coefficients -- then any complex roots (o
r factors) must occur in conjugate pairs.  For example, both the compl
ex factors of " }{TEXT 288 5 "F, G " }{TEXT -1 4 "and " }{TEXT 289 2 "
H " }{TEXT -1 236 "(above) all occurred in conjugate pairs.  Demonstra
te this theorem by creating three new polynomials, name them F1, G1 an
d H1, of degree 5, 6 and 7, resp., and show that the any complex facto
rs of F1, G1 and H1 occur in conjugate pairs." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 49 "F1 :=17*x^5+
2*x^4-21*x^3+101;\nfactor(F1,complex);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 
20 "6#>%#F1G,**&\"#<\"\"\")%\"xG\"\"&F(F(*&\"\"#F()F*\"\"%F(F(*&\"#@F(
)F*\"\"$F(!\"\"\"$,\"F(" }}{PARA 12 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,$*.$\"#<\"
\"!\"\"\",&%\"xGF($\"+%Q(Gb;!\"*F(F(,&F*F(^$$\"++a<_\\!#5$\"+s8\">?\"F
-F(F(,&F*F(^$F0$!+s8\">?\"F-F(F(,&F*F(^$$!+.x.k7F-$\"+[P1asF2F(F(,&F*F
(^$F;$!+[P1asF2F(F(F(" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 61 "G1 :=2*x^6-2*x^5-2*x^4-2*x^3-2*x^2-
2*x-2;\nfactor(G1,complex);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%#G1G,
0*&\"\"#\"\"\")%\"xG\"\"'F(F(*&F'F()F*\"\"&F(!\"\"*&F'F()F*\"\"%F(F/*&
F'F()F*\"\"$F(F/*&F'F()F*F'F(F/*&F'F(F*F(F/F'F/" }}{PARA 12 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6#,$*0$\"\"#\"\"!\"\"\",&%\"xGF($\"+$)44.%)!#5F(F(,&F*F(^
$$\"+l!*G>YF-$\"+!yV9>(F-F(F(,&F*F(^$F0$!+!yV9>(F-F(F(,&F*F(^$$!+S.#H!
RF-$\"+jlhy\")F-F(F(,&F*F(^$F:$!+jlhy\")F-F(F(,&F*F($\"+VGe$)>!\"*!\"
\"F(F(" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 32 "H1 :=x^7-29;\nfac
tor(H1,complex);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%#H1G,&*$)%\"xG\"
\"(\"\"\"F*\"#H!\"\"" }}{PARA 12 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*0,&%\"xG\"\"
\"^$$\"+#3^vX\"!\"*$\"+pg>>q!#5F&F&,&F%F&^$F($!+pg>>qF-F&F&,&F%F&^$$\"
+()Q&)*f$F-$\"+S!*>x:F*F&F&,&F%F&^$F4$!+S!*>x:F*F&F&,&F%F&^$$!+Xml35F*
$\"+Fa\"[E\"F*F&F&,&F%F&^$F>$!+Fa\"[E\"F*F&F&,&F%F&$\"+_'fxh\"F*!\"\"F
&" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 115 "For demonstration purposes it is v
ery handy to be able to construct polynomials with predetermined roots
.  Use the " }{TEXT 258 6 "expand" }{TEXT -1 58 " command to construct
 a polynomial with roots   -2, 5, 5, " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "-1/2" "6#,$*&\"
\"\"F%\"\"#!\"\"F'" }{TEXT -1 71 ", 1+I and  1-I.  (Here the \"5, 5\" \+
indicates that 5 is a \"double root\".)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 
"" }}{EXCHG {PARA 15 "" 0 "" {TEXT 35 6 "expand" }{TEXT -1 113 " has a
n interface that allows the user to make a function known to expand in
 the following way: if the procedure " }{TEXT 35 10 "`expand/f`" }
{TEXT -1 27 " is defined, then the call " }{TEXT 35 13 "expand(f(x));
" }{TEXT -1 33 " will generate the function call " }{TEXT 35 14 "`expa
nd/f`(x);" }{TEXT -1 1 " " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 34 "expand(f(x))(-2,5,5,-1/2,1+I,1-I);
" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,(*$)--%\"xG6#F(6(!\"#\"\"&F,#!\"
\"\"\"#^$\"\"\"F1^$F1F.\"\"$F1F1*$)F&F/F1F.*&F/F1F&F1F." }}}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT 312 2 "kp" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 8 "1.  Okay" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 8 "2.  Okay" }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "3.  " }}{PARA 257 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 27 "Factor ea
ch polynomial and " }{TEXT 313 9 "determine" }{TEXT -1 156 " whether M
aple was able to find enough linear factors to demonstrate the above a
ssertion about the appropriate number of linear factors.   Did you do \+
this??" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 50 
"Did not construct polynomial with specified roots." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 3 "6/6" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 3 "4/4" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "8/10" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 314 5 "18/20" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 46 "4.  Binomial Theorem.  Use the Maple command  " }{TEXT 290 6 "e
xpand" }{TEXT 256 2 "  " }{TEXT -1 34 "to calculate the expansion of  \+
   " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(a+b)^n;" "6#),&%\"aG\"\"\"%\"bGF&%\"nG" }{TEXT 
-1 63 "    for values n=1..10 .  In each case use the Maple command   \+
" }{TEXT 257 7 "coeffs " }{TEXT 292 1 " " }{TEXT -1 84 "to pick off th
e coefficients.   For example,  if n=5 we would execute the following:
" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 27 "expand((a+b)^5);\ncoeffs
(%);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,.*$)%\"aG\"\"&\"\"\"F(*(F'F()
F&\"\"%F(%\"bGF(F(*(\"#5F()F&\"\"$F()F,\"\"#F(F(*(F.F()F&F2F()F,F0F(F(
*(F'F(F&F()F,F+F(F(*$)F,F'F(F(" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6(\"#5
\"\"&F#\"\"\"F%F$" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 28 "Do the rest from 1 \+
to 10.   " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 31 "Note:  it is possible to use
 a " }{TEXT 291 9 "for loop " }{TEXT -1 69 " to simplify this task sin
ce we are doing a repetitive calculation.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 29 "Note:  Also, the the command " }{TEXT 293 6 "coeffs" }{TEXT -1 
15 " unfortunately " }{TEXT 294 8 "does not" }{TEXT -1 36 " pick off t
he coefficients in order." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "The " }{TEXT 260 16 "Binomial Theorem" }{TEXT -1 
66 " gives a formula for finding the coefficients of the expansion of \+
" }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(a+b)^n;" "6#),&%\"aG\"\"\"%\"bGF&%\"nG" }{TEXT -1 
10 "  for any " }{TEXT 295 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 53 ".  It is relatively obv
ious that the coefficient of  " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "a^k*b^(n-k);" "6#*&)%
\"aG%\"kG\"\"\")%\"bG,&%\"nGF'F&!\"\"F'" }{TEXT -1 19 "  for any value
 of " }{TEXT 296 1 "k" }{TEXT -1 11 " from 0 to " }{TEXT 297 1 "n" }
{TEXT -1 46 " is given by the number of ways we can choose " }{TEXT 
